data.name: Aleoids_01
data.value: has upright clumps of long serrated leaves, which can open up to expose a reproductive organ containing tiny round seeds.

data.name: Aleoids_02
data.value: has an interleaved crown of mottled leaves that can grow to head height, with explosive seed pods emerging on long protruding stalks.

data.name: Aleoids_03
data.value: has long spiky leaves that can reach over two metres high surrounding a single reproductive organ on a long central stalk.

data.name: Aleoids_04
data.value: have a circle of upturned leaves marked with patterns, surrounding a bright fleshy pod with darker markings which matures in their centre.

data.name: Aleoids_05
data.value: has wide flat leaves on a heavy bark base that can reach huge sizes. and sprout a dome-shaped reproductive organ at their peak.

data.name: Bacterial_01
data.value: thrive on sunlight in atmospheres rich with carbon dioxide. They cause blanket coloration across a planetary surface.

data.name: Bacterial_02
data.value: survives exclusively on atmospheric helium. They are distinguished by a radial pattern extending outward from the colony’s centre.

data.name: Bacterial_03
data.value: thrive on the heat generated by carbon-based volcanic activity and appear as long swirling ridges on the surface.

data.name: Bacterial_04
data.value: converts energy from neon-based atmospheres, creating looping whirls of bright colour.

data.name: Bacterial_05
data.value: survive on worlds with argon—based atmospheres, and appear as a collection of tight loops on the ground.

data.name: Bacterial_06
data.value: Is found in ammonia-based atmospheres that lives in sunlight. A colony’s appearance resembles an intricate maze.

data.name: Bacterial_07
data.value: appear as an intricate web pattern. They thrive in proximity to helium-based, iron-based and silicate-based volcanic sites.

data.name: Bacterial_08
data.value: can be found in nitrogen atmospheres, and form a shapeless mass across the surface.

data.name: Bacterial_09
data.value: are dependent upon oxygen atmospheres, which creates random swirling patterns across the ground.

data.name: Bacterial_10
data.value: thrives on atmospheric methane, appearing as a network of linked bubble paiterns.

data.name: Bacterial_11
data.value: convert geothermal heat from nitrogen-based volcanic sites into energy. They appear as long interlinked strands across the surface.

data.name: Bacterial_12
data.value: is a sunlight-converting bacterial species on worlds with atmospheres dominated by water and sulphur dioxide. Their colonies resemble a brain-shaped mass of smaller connected cells.

data.name: Bacterial_13
data.value: appear as an intricate web pattern. They thrive in proximity to helium-based, iron-based and silicate-based volcanic sites.

data.name: Cactoid_01
data.value: can reach over three metres in height. They are composed of multiple growths that sprout sealed pods at their peaks, which open up to distribute seeds.

data.name: Cactoid_02
data.value: appears as a squat growth with a latficecl upper surface, which eventually produces a cluster of seed pods.

data.name: Cactoid_03
data.value: appear as a tall collection of cylinders linked by an undulating membrane and topped with a spiky crown. They often have a spiny life-form attached that is thought to form a symbiotic relationship with the larger organism, although the nature of this is not understood.

data.name: Cactoid_04
data.value: has a globular base, from which extend vertical cylinders that can reach over four metres. Rounded pods grow in clusters along the cylinders, which break open to scatter seeds.

data.name: Cactoid_05
data.value: appears as a swollen five-sided growth, reaching over two metres high and topped with an intersected crown.

data.name: Clypeus_01
data.value: grows a broad, tear-shaped shield to protect the sensitive organism from extreme sunlight. The shield’s ridges help to direct Water droplets down into the soil.

data.name: Clypeus_02
data.value: produces a curved shield that resembles a large pearl in shape and texture. Up to three central organisms grow within it upon a supporting bed of leaves.

data.name: Clypeus_03
data.value: grows an angular shield with a mirrored exterior to protect the spiky organisms. This species can be found on planets orbiting their parent star at a distance of 5 AU or greater.

data.name: Conchas_01
data.value: relies on heat sources to survive. As the bisected growth increases in size. it sprouts a single stalk topped with an array of luminous fronds that facilitate metabolism.

data.name: Conchas_02
data.value: are found on worlds with nitrogen-based atmospheres. Their rounded rock-like structure splits part to extend long stalks topped with loops.

data.name: Conchas_03
data.value: thrives in atmospheres rich with carbon dioxide. The lip-like upper opening cracks apart to allow a vertical growth of spiky leaves and bright seeds to stretch upward.

data.name: Conchas_04
data.value: resembles a ridged, bisected egg until they crack in half, allowing a thin stalk to sprout from its fleshy insides. This is covered with cloughnut—shaped pods that create locations for chemical exchange.

data.name: Electricae_01
data.value: extends a tip of four connected loops above the ice, each covered with brightly luminous fronds. This species is typically found on planets orbiting bright white stars.

data.name: Electricae_02
data.value: protrude bioluminescent stalks that radiate out in all directions. It is thought that this species may have an unspecified link with the proximity of nebulae to its host planet.

data.name: Fonticulus_01
data.value: Is found in atmospheres dominated by neon, appearing as a pyramid—shaped cluster of frilled sections.

data.name: Fonticulus_02
data.value: thrive in argon atmospheres, and can reach four metres in height. They feature huge leaf-like structures to capture sunlight for conversion to energy.

data.name: Fonticulus_03
data.value: can he found on ice worlds with argon-rich atmospheres. They produce broad hoop-shaped structures to better reflect weak sunlight onto themselves for photosynthesis.

data.name: Fonticulus_04
data.value: exists in atmospheres with a heavy concentration of nitrogen. Growing up along the main stalk are bright gem-like pods. which can break off and create new colonies.

data.name: Fonticulus_05
data.value: exists on worlds with oxygen atmospheres. They produce coiling wave-shaped structures which tilt toward sunlight.

data.name: Fonticulus_06
data.value: thrives in methane—based atmospheres, sprouting a cluster of cylindrical tubes directly from the ice.

data.name: Fumerolas_01
data.value: Is found near sites of carbon—based volcanism, appearing as a thin upright tube. An inner organism protrudes from an opening at its peak to increase heat absorption.

data.name: Fumerolas_02
data.value: is an exception among its kin. This fumerola species seems to have an arbitrary preference of specific volcanism types which have yet to be explicitly linked in any way. They appear as long vertical stalks with smaller fronds that can stretch out.

data.name: Fumerolas_03
data.value: prefers nitrogen-based volcanism. They produce an ovoid organism with dotted markings, which sits on top of a thin stalk.

data.name: Fumerolas_04
data.value: can be found near sites of water-based volcanic activity. They appear as small dark clusters with ridged folds that trap heat within.

data.name: Fungoids_01
data.value: produces vertical clusters interspersed with spore pods atop thin stalks. allowing them to break off and scatter to reproduce elsewhere.

data.name: Fungoids_02
data.value: thrives on geothermal energy. and can produce two-metre high tower structures composed of tightly clustered cylinders.

data.name: Fungoids_03
data.value: features clusters of mottled bubble-shaped growths atop a central stalk. These contain spores that can be exposed to the winds to facilitate distribution.

data.name: Fungoids_04
data.value: resembles an upturned jellyfish, emerging from a solid base buried within the substrate. The exposed part is dominated by fleshy reproductive organisms that shed organic tissue. This tissue can float on the light breeze and form a new organism if it lands in the right location.

data.name: Osseus_01
data.value: can grow to over six metres across. They produce wide ridged frills for metabolic interactions including aosorbing sunlight for energy production.

data.name: Osseus_02
data.value: appears as half-buried discs with radial patterns, which may resemble natural rook formations from a distance. They absorb geothermal energy from below the surface as well as available heat sources above ground.

data.name: Osseus_03
data.value: produces coiling spiral structures up to six metres wide. There are ridged folds on their upturned surfaces designed to capture sunlight.

data.name: Osseus_04
data.value: grows a single thick stalk from which emerges a wide, broadly circular, pitted endoskeleton. This structure is designed to dramatically increase the surface area to volume ofthe organism, facilitating chemical capture and chemosynthesis on its catalytically active surface.

data.name: Osseus_05
data.value: produces a stacked series of spiral structures up to about three metres. These ridged features are upturned to better absorb sunlight for photosynthesis.

data.name: Osseus_06
data.value: has a single broad stalk from which extend wide circular structures, with the largest plate capping the top to maximise sunlight absorption.

data.name: Recepta_01
data.value: grows a thick latticed structure for protection. A fine translucent membrane stretches between its gaps, allowing sunlight to penetrate and reach the inner organism for photosynthesis.

data.name: Recepta_02
data.value: produces a thick lattice of trunks in a deltahedron shape. This grows around and above the globular central organism, and helps to capture, retain and focus geothermal heat for thermosynthesis.

data.name: Recepta_03
data.value: has a body that is suspended above ground inside a sphere-shaped translucent membrane. This is filled with chemical-rich ﬂuid that both protects the organism and provides the chemical soup needed for metabolism. Chemical exchange is controlled actively through the membrane and passively through the extensive root structure.

data.name: Shrubs_01
data.value: appears as a bush of leaves with a similar texture to seaweed. Seeds are extended on long stalks and protected by a cage formation until ready to germinate.

data.name: Shrubs_02
data.value: has vivid colouration when young that alters as it matures, its upper branches produce lines of small pea-like seed pods.

data.name: Shrubs_03
data.value: has an almost metallic shine to its small leaves. Along its upper branches grow spherical spores, which each have a star-shaped opening to increase germination.

data.name: Shrubs_04
data.value: gives the appearance of flames, with vivid upright fronds extended from multiple stalks. The fronds are dotted with disc-sha ped spores that are distributed by the wind.

data.name: Shrubs_05
data.value: combines broad branches with long thin stalks, along which grow clusters of lightweight seed pods that are scaitered by light winds.

data.name: Shrubs_06
data.value: produces clusters of upright intertwining branches, which are crowned with bright seed sacks.

data.name: Shrubs_07
data.value: Is characterised by its spiky lower branches surrounding a thick central column, which is clotted with spores and with a dark crown.

data.name: Stratum_01
data.value: appears as a mixture of tight concentric ring patterns and mottled proto-leaves in a mixture of dark hues.

data.name: Stratum_02
data.value: blends thick overlapping vines with irregular growths. with varying colours appearing in bands or streaks.

data.name: Stratum_03
data.value: gives the appearance of overlapping rock plateaus, each with narrow bands of colouration.

data.name: Stratum_04
data.value: has a vaguely octopoid shape. Their pale semi-translucent upper domes can reveal colourful inner organisms, which contrast with their darker outstretched tentacles.

data.name: Stratum_05
data.value: appears as a series of unconnected ovoid sha pes across the ground, which are the protruding tips of the larger subterranean organism.

data.name: Stratum_06
data.value: displays fleshy ovoid shapes that are connected in a narrow pattern across the ground. These are covered with streaks of round photosynthetic cells that absorb sunlight.

data.name: Stratum_07
data.value: has a thick rock-like outer shell, covered with an irregular lattice of brighter cells that absorb sunlight for photosynthesis.

data.name: Stratum_08
data.value: forms broad interconnected ring structures, which are composed of narrow ridges to capture sunlight.

data.name: Tubus_01
data.value: Is formed from hollow vertical cylinders that can reach heights of six metres. Mature specimens are capped with a downtu rned crown that can distribute seeds on the wind across a wide area.

data.name: Tubus_02
data.value: grows a cluster of hollow stalks composed of rigid segments. Over time these become capped with a growth that flowers and produces seeds.

data.name: Tubus_03
data.value: extends pale vertical stalks composed of rigid modules. Colourful fronds frequently appear in the gaps between segments and aid with controlling gaseous exchange.

data.name: Tubus_04
data.value: is composed of squat tubes growing into a vertical spire. The upper pods of mature specimens produce explosive seed pods on their outer skin.

data.name: Tubus_05
data.value: has narrow pale segments and fronds growing between each module. A wide crown of leaves at the peak hold spores on their undersides, to germinate across a wide area.

data.name: Tussocks_01
data.value: extends large seed pods on thin stems above a cluster of bright leaves.

data.name: Tussocks_02
data.value: blends tough lower stalks with taller willowy reeds, which produce small pale spores.

data.name: Tussocks_03
data.value: produces thick intertwined leaves, above which sprout narrow stems crowned with seed pods.

data.name: Tussocks_04
data.value: has tall sharp reeds reaching about two metres, characterised by narrow markings along their length.

data.name: Tussocks_05
data.value: has very thin stalks carrying twin sets of seed sacks along their entire length, resembling links on a chain.

data.name: Tussocks_06
data.value: has feather-shaped growths surrounding a single segmented stem which when mature is crowned with colourful seeds.

data.name: Tussocks_07
data.value: sprouts serrated leaves around thick stalks that produce dark seed pods.

data.name: Tussocks_08
data.value: Is characterised by leaves with a distinctive striped pattern that are bisected like a snake’s tongue. Mature versions also sprout smaller leaves which produce spores.

data.name: Tussocks_09
data.value: sprouts tapering leaves, with tips covered with colourful seed pods.

data.name: Tussocks_10
data.value: blends thick segmented lower growths with longer. narrower leaves. Mature versions have pale spores along the upper branches.

data.name: Tussocks_11
data.value: has leaves that have a thick segmented lower half and a willowy upper half. Mature versions produce separate stalks that carry ovoid organisms clotted with spores.

data.name: Tussocks_12
data.value: has thin tough leaves marked with dark stripes. From these sprout taller stalks with small leaves, from which seeds are released to the winds.

data.name: Tussocks_13
data.value: resembles a patch of tough. wiry grasses. Taller stalks carrying disc-shaped seed pods rise above the main organism when mature.

data.name: Tussocks_14
data.value: has thin reeds clustered around a central stalk. which is eventually crowned with spores.

data.name: Tussocks_15
data.value: is a squat cluster of leaves resembling thick matted hair. From the top of these sprout thick pods that carw a number of round beans.
